Headlines.Headline: CREDIT MARKETS: Corporate Issuers Rush To Sell Debt As Sentiment Improves

PARAGRAPH.#text: Stocks rose, Treasurys fell and corporate bond issuers rushed to issue debt Thursday amid signs that Greece may cancel plans for a referendum on its financial bailout. Companies sold more than $9 billion in debt, as borrowers looked to take advantage of improved investor sentiment. Financial markets in general have been attuned to the barrage of headlines concerning Europe's sovereign-debt woes, moving up or down depending on the latest development. Corporate borrowers returned to the debt markets in droves Thursday, offering more than $9 billion of new investment-grade bonds in a window between volatility earlier this week and an expected gusher of issuance next week.

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Deborah Levine Treasury prices dropped on Tuesday, weakening after briefly paring an earlier decline following the U.S. government's auction of 10-year notes. Though the 10-year sale received strong demand, especially from a group that includes foreign investors, traders worried about the potential demand for Wednesday's sale of 30-year Treasury bonds. Yields on the current 10-year notes (UST10Y), which move inversely to prices, rose 9 basis points to 2.65%. A basis point is 0.01%. Yields on 2-year notes (UST2YR) jumped 4 basis points to 0.44%, a reversal from a session low of 0.38% earlier.

PARAGRAPH.#text: (This article was originally published Tuesday.) NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Trying to determine turning points in the real-estate market has never been simple. But now that two influential research firms are pushing very different views of the market, some investors are scratching their heads. Green Street Advisors, a Newport Beach, Calif., firm that closely tracks real-estate investment trusts, says prices of commercial real estate hit bottom in mid-2009 and have been slowly rising ever since. Not so, says Moody's Investors Service, which is telling clients that it is still too early to call a bottom and advises caution.

Headlines.Author: Chad Bray
Headlines.Headline: GMAC's Merkin, Ascot Fund Sued Over Madoff Investments

PARAGRAPH.#text: (This article was originally published Tuesday.) NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--New York Law School filed an investor lawsuit against J. Ezra Merkin, chairman of lender GMAC Financial Services, one of his funds and its auditor on Tuesday over investments made through Bernard L. Madoff Investment Securities LLC, whose founder has been charged in a massive Ponzi scheme. The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in Manhattan, alleges recklessness, gross negligence and breach of fiduciary duties by Merkin, who also heads money-management firm Gabriel Partners; the fund, Ascot Partners LP; and its auditor, BDO Seidman LLP.

#text: British Airways

is considering a roughly $2.9 billion sale and leaseback of its property portfolio as a way of cutting debt and increasing its cash reserves, according to several UK papers. Chief executive Rod Eddington told the Sunday Times that if such a sale were to go through, it would come from BA's property at Heathrow, including its new $435.8 million headquarters. Headlines.Headline:
Goldman Sachs Earnings
Rise by 58% to a Record

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Goldman Sachs's
 fiscal third-quarter
profit soared 58%, auguring good news for other Wall Street firms. The
industry bellwether had earnings of $932 million in the quarter ended Aug.
31.

Headlines.Headline: Boston Properties Sets Buy

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Boston Properties
, Mortimer
Zuckerman's real-estate investment company, agreed to acquire a New York
office complex in Manhattan from Bankers Trust for $321.3 million, its
first acquisition since going public earlier this summer.
